      "text/plain": [
       "AIMessage(content='**Car – a concise definition**\\n\\nA **car** (short for *automobile*) is a self‑propelled road vehicle designed primarily for transporting people (and sometimes light cargo) on public highways and streets. It typically has four wheels, an internal‑combustion engine or electric motor, and a seating capacity of 1‑8 occupants.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Core Characteristics\\n\\n| Feature | Typical Details |\\n|---------|-----------------|\\n| **Power source** | • Internal‑combustion engine (petrol, diesel, hybrid)  <br>• Battery‑electric motor (BEV)  <br>• Fuel‑cell (hydrogen) |\\n| **Drive layout** | Front‑wheel drive (FWD), rear‑wheel drive (RWD), all‑wheel drive (AWD/4WD) |\\n| **Body styles** | Sedan, hatchback, coupe, convertible, SUV, crossover, minivan, pickup, etc. |\\n| **Weight** | Roughly 1\\u202f000\\u202f–\\u202f2\\u202f500\\u202fkg (2\\u202f200\\u202f–\\u202f5\\u202f500\\u202flb) for passenger cars |\\n| **Speed** | Typical top speed 150–250\\u202fkm/h (90–155\\u202fmph); high‑performance models exceed 300\\u202fkm/h (186\\u202fmph) |\\n| **Regulations** | Must meet safety (crash, airbags, seat‑belts), emissions, and lighting standards set by national authorities (e.g., NHTSA, UNECE, EPA). |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Main Sub‑systems\\n\\n| Sub‑system | Primary Function |\\n|------------|------------------|\\n| **Powertrain** | Generates and delivers motive force (engine/motor + transmission). |\\n| **Chassis & Suspension** | Supports the body, absorbs road irregularities, and maintains tire contact. |\\n| **Steering** | Allows driver to change direction (rack‑and‑pinion, electric power‑steer). |\\n| **Braking** | Reduces speed (hydraulic disc/drum, ABS, regenerative braking in EVs). |\\n| **Electrical/Electronics** | Battery, wiring, ECU/ECM, infotainment, driver‑assist sensors. |\\n| **Body & Interior** | Provides passenger space, crash protection, aesthetics, climate control. |\\n| **Safety Systems** | Airbags, seat‑belt pretensioners, ESC, collision‑avoidance, ADAS. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Brief Historical Timeline\\n\\n| Era | Milestones |\\n|-----|------------|\\n| **Late 19th\\u202fc.** | Karl Benz builds the *Motorwagen* (1885) – first practical gasoline car. |\\n| **1900‑1920** | Mass production begins (Ford Model\\u202fT, 1908) → affordable cars for the masses. |\\n| **1930‑1950** | Streamlined designs, introduction of automatic transmissions, safety glass. |\\n| **1970‑1990** | Oil crises spur fuel‑efficiency research; emission controls (catalytic converters). |\\n| **1990‑2000** | Rise of electronic engine management, airbags become standard. |\\n| **2000‑2015** | Hybrid vehicles (Toyota Prius) and early electric cars (Nissan Leaf). |\\n| **2015‑present** | Rapid EV adoption, advanced driver‑assist (Tesla Autopilot, GM Super Cruise), connectivity (5G, OTA updates). |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Types of Cars by Powertrain (2024 snapshot)\\n\\n| Powertrain | Typical Range (km) | CO₂ Emissions (g\\u202fkm⁻¹) | Example Models |\\n|------------|-------------------|------------------------|----------------|\\n| **Petrol (ICE)** | 400‑800 | 100‑180 | Toyota Corolla, Volkswagen Golf |\\n| **Diesel (ICE)** | 500‑900 | 80‑150 | BMW 3‑Series Diesel, Mercedes‑C Diesel |\\n| **Hybrid (ICE\\u202f+\\u202fElectric)** | 600‑900 (combined) | 40‑90 | Toyota Prius, Honda CR‑V Hybrid |\\n| **Plug‑in Hybrid (PHEV)** | 50‑80 (electric‑only) + 600‑800 (total) | 30‑70 | Volvo XC90 Recharge, Kia Niro PHEV |\\n| **Battery‑Electric (BEV)** | 200‑600 (single charge) | 0 (tailpipe) | Tesla Model\\u202f3, Hyundai Ioniq\\u202f5 |\\n| **Fuel‑Cell (FCEV)** | 400‑600 (hydrogen) | 0 (tailpipe) | Toyota Mirai, Hyundai Nexo |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Why Cars Matter\\n\\n1. **Mobility & Economy** – Enable personal travel, freight delivery, and support virtually every sector of the modern economy.\\n2. **Urban Planning** – Shape city layouts, parking infrastructure, and public‑transport integration.\\n3. **Technology Platform** – Serve as test‑beds for AI, connectivity, renewable‑energy integration, and advanced materials.\\n4. **Environmental Impact** – Responsible for ~15\\u202f% of global CO₂ emissions (as of 2023); the shift to EVs and stricter standards aims to cut this dramatically.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6. Common Misconceptions\\n\\n| Misconception | Reality |\\n|---------------|---------|\\n| “All cars are gasoline‑powered.” | In 2024, ~30\\u202f% of new registrations are electric or hybrid; gasoline share is falling. |\\n| “Cars are only for personal use.” | Fleet vehicles, ride‑hailing, car‑sharing, and autonomous taxis are growing segments. |\\n| “More horsepower always means a better car.” | Performance is just one factor; safety, efficiency, reliability, and cost of ownership often matter more to most buyers. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 7. Quick FAQ\\n\\n| Question | Answer |\\n|----------|--------|\\n| **What is the difference between a sedan and a hatchback?** | A sedan has a separate trunk compartment; a hatchback’s rear cargo area opens upward with the rear window, offering more flexible cargo space. |\\n| **Can a car run without a driver?** | Fully autonomous (Level\\u202f5) cars do not yet exist in mass production; most “self‑driving” features are Level\\u202f2‑3 driver‑assist systems that still require human supervision. |\\n| **How long does a typical car last?** | With regular maintenance, modern cars often exceed 200,000\\u202fkm (≈125,000\\u202fmi) and can remain on the road for 12‑15\\u202fyears or more. |\\n| **What is “regenerative braking”?** | In EVs and hybrids, the electric motor works as a generator during deceleration, converting kinetic energy back into electrical energy stored in the battery. |\\n| **Is buying an electric car cheaper than a gasoline car?** | Up‑front price is higher, but lower fuel and maintenance costs plus incentives often make total‑cost‑of‑ownership lower over 5‑8\\u202fyears. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### TL;DR\\n\\nA **car** is a four‑wheeled, self‑propelled road vehicle designed for passenger transport. It can be powered by gasoline, diesel, hybrid systems, batteries, or hydrogen, and comes in many body styles (sedan, SUV, hatchback, etc.). Cars combine a powertrain, chassis, steering, brakes, electronics, and safety systems, and they have evolved from the 1880s steam‑ and gasoline‑driven prototypes to today’s high‑tech electric and semi‑autonomous machines. They remain a cornerstone of modern mobility while undergoing rapid transformation toward cleaner, connected, and eventually driver‑less transportation.', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 1692, 'prompt_tokens': 70, 'total_tokens': 1762, 'completion_tokens_details': None, 'prompt_tokens_details': None}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'gpt-oss:120b', 'system_fingerprint': 'fp_ollama', 'id': 'chatcmpl-312', 'finish_reason': 'stop', 'logprobs': None}, id='lc_run--019efe2c-78b6-7420-b26c-6b27025283d9-0', tool_calls=[], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 70, 'output_tokens': 1692, 'total_tokens': 1762, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {}})"
